# Tummy Talk — Paediatric GI Symptom Companion

Shared-tablet app for paediatric GI wards. A clinician sets up a session, hands the
tablet to a child (5–12) and their parent, they answer a fixed set of symptom
questions, and the clinician gets a structured summary plus AI-suggested follow-ups.

**Educational / competition prototype. Not a medical device. No real patient data, ever.**

## Stack
- Framework: Next.js 15 (App Router) + TypeScript, one repo for frontend and backend
- Styling: Tailwind + shadcn/ui (clinician screens); custom inline SVG (child screens)
- Animation: Motion (`motion/react`)
- Validation: Zod, schemas shared between client and server
- Data: Postgres via Supabase
- i18n: next-intl
- LLM: Anthropic API, server-side only
- Package manager: pnpm

## Architecture
- `app/(clinician)/` — setup, review, follow-up approval screens
- `app/(session)/` — child and parent question flow
- `app/api/` — route handlers (the only place server work happens)
- `lib/questions/` — the standard nine definitions, single source of truth
- `lib/schemas/` — Zod schemas for responses, summaries, FHIR output
- `lib/fhir/` — QuestionnaireResponse mapping
- `components/child/` — child-facing visual components (faces scale, body map, Bristol chart)
- `components/clinician/` — clinician-facing components
- `messages/` — i18n message catalogues, one file per locale

## Commands
- Dev: `pnpm dev`
- Test: `pnpm test`
- Typecheck: `pnpm typecheck`
- Lint: `pnpm lint`

## Scope discipline
Build only what the PRD specifies. Do NOT add without being asked:
- Authentication beyond a stubbed clinician identity
- Analytics, telemetry, or third-party trackers
- Native mobile wrappers
- Longitudinal / cross-admission tracking
- Any diagnosis, triage, or clinical recommendation feature

## Workflow
- Commit after each working feature
- Never commit `.env` or any file containing keys
- Seed and demo data must be obviously fictional (e.g. "Test Patient A", DOB 2015-01-01)
